      </h3>
      <div class="text-[11px] sm:text-xs text-slate leading-relaxed flex flex-col gap-2.5">
        <p>
          A <strong>MET</strong> (Metabolic Equivalent of Task) is a standard physiological measure used to estimate the energy cost of physical activities. 
          One MET is defined as the energy expended while sitting quietly at rest, equivalent to burning approximately <strong>1 kcal per kilogram of body weight per hour</strong>.
        </p>
        <ul class="list-disc pl-4 flex flex-col gap-1 text-slate font-medium">
          <li><strong>Light Activities (&lt; 3.0 METs):</strong> Slow walking, stretching, light deskwork, or easy yoga.</li>
          <li><strong>Moderate Activities (3.0 to 6.0 METs):</strong> Brisk walking, recreational cycling, casual swimming, or moderate weightlifting.</li>
          <li><strong>Vigorous Activities (&gt; 6.0 METs):</strong> Running, competitive sports, HIIT training, or heavy rowing.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          <strong>Formula Details:</strong> The basic formula uses your weight (in kilograms) and activity duration to calculate absolute energy expenditure: <code>Calories = MET &times; Weight (kg) &times; Duration (hours)</code>. 
          This estimate is useful for planning exercise regimens, but does not capture variations in lean muscle mass, biological sex, age, or mechanical efficiency.
        </p>
